===Etymology===
{{IPAchar|/arataɕi/}} → {{IPAchar|/ataraɕi/}} → {{IPAchar|/ataraɕiki/}} → {{IPAchar|/arataɕiː/}}

In {{w|Old Japanese}}, the original term was {{m|ja|新たし|tr=aratashi}}, composed of older {{m|ja|新た|tr=arata||new}} + adjective-forming suffix {{ja-r|し}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR"/>  This persisted until at least the mid-1200s,<ref name="KDJ"/> and indeed the adjective stem ''arata'' is both modern adjective {{m|ja|新た|tr=arata|pos=''-na'' adjective}} and the root of verbs such as {{m|ja|改める|tr=aratameru||to [[renew]], [[refresh]], [[revise]], or [[reform]] something}}.  See {{m|ja|新た|tr=arata}} for further details of that etymology.

Starting from the 900s, the ''aratashi'' reading began shifting to ''atarashi''.  This [[metathesis]] may have been due to [[conflation]] with {{m|ja|可惜し|tr=atarashi||[[magnificent]], [[excellent]], [[precious]]; [[regrettable]]}}.<ref name="KDJ"/><ref name="DJR"/>  The ''aratashi'' reading then became more and more uncommon in {{w|Early Middle Japanese}}, and the “[[new]], [[modern]], [[fresh]]” sense became the main use, superseding the largely homophonous {{m|ja|可惜し|tr=atarashi}} and pushing it out of common usage.

The modern form is {{ja-adj-shiku|新し|atarashi|nocap=1}}

